Management Revolution or End of Economic Intelligence?
If nothing changes in the governance of large French companies, our fight for the development of economic intelligence will have been futile...
For more than ten years, the attitude of managing large-scale companies towards their employees has been a reminder of the position of companies facing consumers before the marketing revolution: it is a question of getting employees to "values" determined as it once was, of imposing on consumers the products thought by the factory technicians.
By putting the client at the heart of the company, the marketing revolution has handed over the procurement strategies to the site... although the authoritarian temptation to impose disconnected products of customer preference factors comes back on a regular basis!
Demobilization of employees can lead to deadly demoralization.
Suicides in France Telecom, PSA or Renault are only the emerging part of a much more general phenomenon that affects managers in particular.
This demobilisation seriously undermines the development of all the company's intellectual functions, including R&D and, more importantly, economic intelligence.
Indeed, the EI "requires all stakeholders (...) a proactive approach and a prospective vision"; it requires employees to commit themselves to the full infringement of the authoritarian management revenue.
That is why we call for a managerial revolution that would be to put the employees at the centre of the company's concerns in the same way as the client.
The relative usefulness of internal opinion surveys
Will internal opinion surveys – such as Orange's questionnaire to its employees – encourage this revolution in management practices?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
- First of all, because I could see that, in the face of a new situation, all structures finally arrive, after many detours, to do priority... what she has always done.
- Then, because authoritarianism – one of the diseases of power – increases proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most leaders have a simplistic view of human behavior.
From the major engineering schools, they have a mechanical interpretation of psychology.
They adopt, by intellectual comfort, the old life-threatening theory, recently reactivated by the "neurossciences" of the United States and widely disseminated, on their own, by the institutes of studies and the media.
Thus, by suggesting that it is possible to handle the "levers" (sic) of executive engagement, a recent survey of Ipsos published in Le Figaro.fr is strengthening leaders in a mechanistic governance position, inadequate to today's world.
Identify and measure mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises, implies adopting a finalist vision of human behaviour.
It consists of incorporating, in any reasoning or practice of governance, a fundamental finding: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it appears clearly as a means of achieving some of their dreams, ambitions, projects.
Currently, only the studies from the Reasoning Analysis adopt this conception of employee motivations.
These studies have shown that they judge their business based on a predetermined doxa that allows them, through their perceived image of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to carry out their life plans.
Through the identification and measurement of these mobilisation factors, business leaders can control, predict and anticipate their "social performance" and deliver their management of human resources "to the place".
They thus create a favourable ground for the concerted development of a robust and effective economic intelligence.
