75% of working mothers have had professional problems because of their maternity
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of young generations who want to be mothers.
This is what the study "Feverhood and career of women in Spain" carried out by the CSIC in collaboration with the Instituto de la Mujer (Instituto de la Mujer) shows.
The survey, conducted out of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75, leaves no doubt: 75 per cent of working mothers have had their career limited due to maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences between the start of life in couples and the number of children, whether or not the woman works and the type of employment.
Those who have no activity outside the home, work part-time or have a unstable job, get married earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, resist entry into married life and the first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women between 35 and 49 years of fixed employment have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after settling in a couple. This figure is 4.1 among those working in the public sector. "This data shows that women with stable employment have needed more time in their lives to get it, which has led them to push back the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of employment exerted has a strong influence on maternity, but less on the date of common start of life," says CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that widens the age of marriage for women and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of training, the more they get married and have their first child late.
The difference also remains among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49-year-old group, those who did elementary and higher studies were mothers for the first time at 25.1 and at an average of 32.1 years.
"Another distinction also appears among women, depending on their level of education.
While those who have completed elementary education get married and have their first child before finding stable employment, those who have done middle-level or higher-level studies reverse this program and give priority to obtaining stable work as a precondition for marriage and the arrival of a child," says Delgado.
