Emergency braking assistance is now mandatory
As has been done with the ABS braking system and as will be done with the ESP stability control, emergency braking aid systems will be a mandatory component on European cars.
They are already mandatory on newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest of vehicles a period of shortage has been fixed until the end of February 2011.
The aim of the measure, imposed by the European Union, is to strengthen pedestrian protection, even if, by its mode of action, it can also help to avoid many back crashes.
The emergency braking assistant acts by increasing pressure on the brakes in the event of an emergency detected by the system thanks to the driver's kick.
But the latter does not always keep the pressure to the end.
According to a study carried out by the Bosch car manufacturer, one third of drivers involved in an accident could not rely on the brake before the collision, and half of them had not benefited from all its strength.
Up to 1 100 accidents
The aid intervention, on the other hand, requires the maximum brake system, reducing the distance the car needs to stop.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with such elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents in which pedestrians are involved could be avoided each year.
This reduction would be even more important with the popularization of the so-called emergency braking systems: it is estimated that one in four disasters with wounded would be avoided.
